SSBDESC.SSBDESC_TEXT_NARRATIVE: This is primarily a studio course. This means that you will learn about the fundamentals of art through experience and experimentation. This course is designed for the beginner. Therefore, basic knowledge areas will be introduced. However, even though this is not an advanced art course, aesthetic and good craftsmanship does apply to all c ompleted art projects. You will become familiar with the fundamentals of art, as well as exploring "trial and error" art methods. Through determination and an open mind, you will increase your creativity and discover more interesting ways to solve art problems. With a willingness to work and an open mind, your experie nces in this class will be memorable in a positive way.br

Decision Making for Leaders explores the process of decision making; how decisions are made and how they should be made, giving the participants the techniques and frameworks to adopt a structured and systematic process when making critical business choices. Participants will be able to ask the correct questions to identify and tackle the right problem; separating the relevant information from �noise� and avoiding the common pitfalls and decision traps. Participants will learn the process The programme is aimed at business leaders who make critical business choices and want to learn better frameworks for making the right decision. The programme will give the participants the tools and skills to perform better in their specific functional area by broadening their understanding of their business and the strategic environment in which they work.

pObjectives: English 226 provides an examination of works within British literature that mark central tendencies within multiple genres from the late 1700s to today. During the course students become familiar with literary works exemplifying Romanticism, Victorianism, modernism, postmodernism, and postcolonialism. We will examine works by considering their conventions, terms, and broad contexts for the works, which include the authors concerns and culture as well as the influence of literary and artistic movements. The literature and authors are also considered as acting with or reacting against historical, political, social, artistic, and other phenomena which can exert influence on works and authors. The course also considers works i n light of various critical approaches and provides guidance on writing about literature within academic contexts, including the use of sources and the MLA format./p
pStudents will demonstrate at least competency in the following skills by written and oral communication in the course exams, papers, and class discussion: ul liawareness of and ability to use appropriately the applicable literary terms we cover/li liability to identify authors, titles, conventions, and concerns of individual works we cover /li liability to write papers that are appropriate to academic contexts on the literature we cover /li liability to use and cite a variety of sources correctly in the MLA format /li liawareness of external influences (historical, gender, economic, and others) on a work /li/ul /p pStudents will also demonstrate their research and presentation abilities by researching and presenting information on one author we study when we begin that author./p
pGrades: Grades are divided equally among four written exams, two researched papers (3-5 pages), the presentation mentioned above, a number of shorter (1-2 page) responses throughout the term (used in place of quizzes). All exams are based upon the texts assigned as covered in class and upon class notes. The shorter responses are introduced to enliven readings and participation and are equal to one paper or exam grade./P
p1-2 Page responses:Questions for these will be provided in class for the next class meeting. They are graded Excellent, Strong, Satisfactory, or Weak for the following points: Brevity (fitting within the stated length of the response); Specificity (answering the questions specifically, with specific but brief examples); Content (answering questions with some substance, thoughfulness, and reasoning). /p
pStudying for exams: I recommend studying individually first and thereafter with other students as a group, filling in gaps in each others notes and/or understanding. To assess high level trends that drive mass marketing efforts.

Class participation will be judged on the basis of the three individual exercises assigned during the term as well as in class contributions.
Some of the characteristics of effective class participation are suggested by these questions:
Is the student prepared and attentive? Do comments reveal an understanding of the course concepts and the dynamics of the class discussion?
Is the student a good receiver? Are the points made relevant to the discussion? Are they linked to the comments of others? Is the student willing to interact with other class members?
Is the student an effective communicator? Are concepts presented in a concise and convincing fashion?

General analysis of management and organizational behavior from a systems point of view, including classical organizational theory and management, organizational behavior, and management science; environmental forces; planning, organizing, and control processes; motivation, incentives, leadership, communication, and i nterpersonal relations; and discussion of production and decision-making and mathematical models.

Understanding the behavior of employees in work organizations; particular attention to the motivation of individuals to join and perform in organizations and to employee satisfaction with elements of the work environment; and emphasis on various management strategies to modify employee motivation and satisfaction.
Understanding of complex organizations; particular attention to ways of dividing work, achieving coordination, and issues connected with change and adaptation.

Gives a general analysis of the structure of retailing emphasizing the retailing environment and operating efficiencies; includes patronage behavior, merchandise control, pricing, promotion, location, and vendor relations; and gives special attention to emerging trends in retailing.

Focuses on the techniques and methods of marketing research; emphasizes primarily survey research and experimental design; and offers students the opportunity to apply techniques to real-world situations.

Examines the analysis, planning, and forms of organization that are associated with the buying functions in business. Major focus on the principal issues involved in the procurement of raw materials, components, equipment, operating supplies, and services. Also treats the unique aspects of institutional and government purchasing. Case problems constitute a major vehicle of instruction.

Studies the factors affecting customer behavior in household and organizational markets and their relevance for marketing management planning and analysis; provides an overview of explanations of consumption differences anchored in socioeconomic, demographic, cultural, and psychological processes; and surveys buyer decision-making processes and their implications for marketing strategy.

The role of pricing in contemporary marketing and major pricing decisions facing the firm; theoretical, economic, and practical methods and models for setting prices; pricing new products, initiating price changes, and responding to competitive pricing; the relationship of pricing objectives and strategies to the goals of the firm; and sealed bidding for contracts.

Introduces the general area of industrial marketing; examines the nature of industrial markets especially as they compare to consumer markets and emphasizes such factors as the demand for industrial goods, marketing intelligence systems for industrial firms, marketing strategy in industrial markets, and analyses and control of industrial marketing programs; integrates important concepts from sales management and business l ogistics throughout the course; uses case studies.

Introduces the use of persuasive personal communication in attracting and retaining customers. Uses experiential learning exercises to address principles and techniques of personal selling and the administration of the selling function as it relates to the development of marketing strategy and the achievement of corpor ate objectives.

Integrative study of methods and chaos models for marketing decision-making; emphasizes the application of analytical tools and behavioral and quantitative models to marketing decision-making. Uses lectures, case studies and simulation exercises

Analyzes marketing strategy across national boundaries, the problems of marketing within foreign countries, and the coordination of global marketing programs. Includes problems faced by the exporter, licensor, joint venture, and multinational firm. The full range of market activities are discussed from a global p erspective.
